Section 15: Partitions

Definition

Let BBBB be a set. A partition of BBBB is a collection of non-empty, pairwise disjoint subsets of BBBB whose union is equal to BBBB.

Remarks

  1. Each member of the partition is a subset of BBBB, called the part.
  2. The parts of the partition are non-empty, pairwise disjoint
  3. The union of all parts is equal to BBBB

The Division Principle

Let RRRR be an equivalence relation on a finite set AAAA. If all equivalence classes have the same cardinality mmmm, then the number of equivalence classes is \frac{|A|}{m}∣A∣m\frac{|A|}{m}m∣A∣​.

Anagram with more repeated letters

\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}1◯\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}1​◯​​ How many different anagrams can be made from "SUCCESS"?

Solution: \underline{S_1}\space\underline{U}\space\underline{C_1}\space\underline{C_2}\space\underline{S_2}\space\underline{S_3} = 7!S1‾ U‾ C1‾ C2‾ S2‾ S3‾=7!\underline{S_1}\space\underline{U}\space\underline{C_1}\space\underline{C_2}\space\underline{S_2}\space\underline{S_3} = 7!S1​​ U​ C1​​ C2​​ S2​​ S3​​=7!

Answer is: \frac{7!}{3!2!}7!3!2!\frac{7!}{3!2!}3!2!7!​ where 3!3!3!3! is the repetition of "S" and 2!2!2!2! is the repetition of "C"

\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}2◯\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}2​◯​​ If the first and last letter must be "S"?

\underline{1(S)}\space\underline{5}\space\underline{4}\space\underline{3}\space\underline{2}\space\underline{1}\space\underline{1(S)} = \frac{5!}{2!}1(S)‾ 5‾ 4‾ 3‾ 2‾ 1‾ 1(S)‾=5!2!\underline{1(S)}\space\underline{5}\space\underline{4}\space\underline{3}\space\underline{2}\space\underline{1}\space\underline{1(S)} = \frac{5!}{2!}1(S)​ 5​ 4​ 3​ 2​ 1​ 1(S)​=2!5!​ where 2!2!2!2! is for the repetition of "C"

Note that because there are two instances of "S" that are fixed, the repetition of "S" is cancelled out and not included in the calculation.

\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}3◯\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {3}}}3​◯​​ If only the first letter must be "S"?

\underline{1(S)}\space\underline{6}\space\underline{5}\space\underline{4}\space\underline{3}\space\underline{2}\space\underline{1} = \frac{6!}{2!2!}1(S)‾ 6‾ 5‾ 4‾ 3‾ 2‾ 1‾=6!2!2!\underline{1(S)}\space\underline{6}\space\underline{5}\space\underline{4}\space\underline{3}\space\underline{2}\space\underline{1} = \frac{6!}{2!2!}1(S)​ 6​ 5​ 4​ 3​ 2​ 1​=2!2!6!​ where both 2!2!2!2! are from the repetition of "S" and "C"

Note that because only one of the "S"s are fixed, there are still two that can repeat, so that repetition is shown by 2!2!2!2!

\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}1◯\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {1}}}1​◯​​ How many anagrams can be made from the word "MISSISSIPPI"?

\frac{11!}{4!4!2!}11!4!4!2!\frac{11!}{4!4!2!}4!4!2!11!​ where 4!4!4!4! is for the repetition of "S" and "I" respectively, and 2!2!2!2! is for "P"

\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}2◯\raisebox{.5pt}{\textcircled{\raisebox{-.9pt} {2}}}2​◯​​ If the first and last letters are "P"?

\frac{9!}{4!4!}9!4!4!\frac{9!}{4!4!}4!4!9!​ where 4!4!4!4! is for the repetition of "S" and "I"

Note that because the first and last letters are fixed to "P", that repetition is cancelled out and therefore not included in the calculation.
